The Building a Pipeline of Biodiesel Technicians for Careers in Fields and Cities   Grant at Lewis and Clark Community College (L&amp;C) in Godfrey, Illinois developed an educational pathway preparing students to meet the challenges of the growing and evolving diesel/biodiesel technology sector.  Directed by principal investigator Professor Christopher E. Reynolds, M.S.Ed., the Diesel/Biodiesel Technology program now serves as the only postsecondary option of its kind available in the Illinois counties Lewis &amp; Clark Community College serves.

The key components of the initiative entail: 1) development of new diesel/biodiesel courses, 2) accreditation approval for a college-level certificate in diesel/biodiesel technology, 3) STEM-based professional development and customized instructional modules for secondary and postsecondary faculty, 4) targeted outreach strategies designed to engage underserved rural and urban students, 5) stackable credentials through a 2+2+2 pathway model; and, 6) work-based learning activities and internships with diesel/biodiesel industry partners.

Key impacts include:

Establishment of Diesel industry representatives for the Lewis &amp; Clark Community College Automotive Technology Advisory Committee;
Development and integration of three (3) credit-bearing courses into the diesel technology curriculum: DTEC 241, Intro to Diesel Engine Repair; DTEC 243, MHDT Brakes, Steering, &amp; Suspension; and DTEC 246 MHDT Electricity &amp; Electronics;
Collaboration with area high schools to establish dual credit for students in high school general education/STEM courses;
Approved by Illinois Community College Board for Certificate of Proficiency in Diesel Technology;
Student/faculty participation in work-based learning with industry partners (e.g., American Lung Association, Bendix Brake Systems, BiState Development [St. Louis' MetroLink public transportation system], Central Illinois Trucking, Agency for Community Transit/Madison Country Transit, Diesel Laptops, VacTruck Rentals, Area Diesel Service, and Illinois Soybean Association).  Experiences included apprenticeships, student employment, onsite observations, as well as onsite and online training; and
High school visits and college recruitment events (on and off-campus).


Grant activities also encouraged the development of private awards for student scholarships through the founder of the Agency for Community Transit/Madison County Transit that will support the development of future diesel service and diagnostic technicians in the Riverbend region.

